        "I have a big zero, boss." Scrap said as he closed the bottom drawer of the last filing cabinet.  "Nothing in here but magazines, reports, blah blah." <br/><br/>I straightened up in my chair and tapped my pen on the desk in front of me.  I had just completed my examination of Dunnit's workstation.<br/><br/>"It's time to move on to the SAN." I said.<br/><br/>"Aroo?" Scrap said excitedly as he magically appeared next to me as if he were powered by some sort of hidden warp drive.<br/><br/>"I hate it when you do that." I whined as I turned my attention back to the workstation.<br/><br/>Scrap scratched the back of his head.  "So, where was Dunnit working on the SAN?  What did you find in /etc/fstab?"<br/><br/>I tapped on the keyboard and brought up the /etc/fstab file from the workstation.<br/><br/><b>[ Note to readers who aren't too UNIX-savy -  The 'man' page for fstab describes fstab as: <br/>"The file fstab contains descriptive information about the various file systems.  fstab is only read by programs, and not written; it is the duty of the system administrator to properly create and maintain this file.  Each filesystem is described on a separate line; fields on each line are separated by tabs or spaces."<br/><br/>In other words, this file tells the computer which filesystems are mapped to what devices, the filesystem used, what options are to be used when mounting (like read-only), and how the system file checker should treat the filesystem.<br/><br/>Example:<br/><br/><i>/dev/md0        /home           ext3    defaults,usrquota,grpquota,errors=remount-ro    0       1</i><br/><br/>In our example, /dev/md0 is a RAID device.  /home is a directory (mount point) where we want the system to put the contents of /dev/md0.  Ext3 is the journaled filesystem of choice for this example, and we want the system to mount the filesystem with several options like quota.  The fifth field is used to tell the system if the 'dump' utility should be used (man 'dump' for more information on dump), and the sixth field tells the system which order the filesystems should be checked on boot.<br/><br/>Knowing this, we return to our story! ]</b><br/><br/>Dunnit's fstab file looked very normal for a linux workstation:<br/><br/><b>/dev/hda3                 /                       ext3    defaults        1 1<br/>/dev/hda1             /boot                   ext2    defaults        1 2<br/>/dev/hda2             /home                   ext3    defaults        1 2<br/>/dev/hda4         swap                    swap    defaults        0 0<br/>/dev/fd0                /media/floppy           auto    pamconsole,exec,noauto,managed 0 0</b><br/><br/><br/>"This is interesting.  None of the SAN volumes are mounted at boot time.  That's a bit unusual for someone that stores all their precious data on a SAN, right?" I queried.<br/><br/>"Hmmm.  I agree, boss.  So the fun part is going to be how do we locate what SAN resources homeboy was using?" Scrap responded.<br/><br/>"Well, if he was manually mounting and unmounting the stuff as needed, then it would be in a shell history file somewhere.  I just realized that I haven't looked at those just yet." I muttered.  I quickly scanned the /etc/passwd file to see what login shells were used by any active accounts.  <br/><br/>"Looks like this is a bash house." I joked as I scanned the file.  Every account (including root) used /bin/bash as their login shell.<br/><br/>I immediately scanned the Encase image for .bash_history files and located two.  One was located inside /root, root's home directory - and the other was in /home/jdunnit.  <br/><br/>A quick scan of /home/jdunnit/.bash_history showed nothing regarding the SAN.  When I dumped the /root/.bash_history file, both Scrap and I giggled like school girls.<br/><br/>Filesystem mount commands.<br/><br/>Lots of them.<hr><br/><p><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20120626081231/http://www.numly.com/numly/verify.asp?id=46950-061031-386635-17"><img alt="numly esn" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20120626081231im_/http://numly.com/numly/icon.asp?id=4695006103138663517" border="0"> 46950-061031-386635-17<br><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20120626081231im_/http://numly.com/numly/barcode.asp?code=4695006103138663517&amp;height=20&amp;width=1&amp;mode=code39"></a><br><br>© 2006 All Rights Reserved.</p>
    </div>    
    <div class="spacer marginleftgutter">
            <hr/>
