<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20120626081231/http://it.toolbox.com/people/unknownuser/" class="size11">Unknown User</a>

<!---->

				
<span class="size11 darkgray">Nov 4, 2006</span>
                
                

            </div>
			<span class="anthracite size13" contentbodystyle="Anthracite">I know about sudoers, Im just saying that what if you want someone to have sudo access but dont want them to be able to 'sudo passwd root' or 'sudo usermod -G admin'

short of aliasing that specific command to some sort of echo warning, or chmod'ing the passwd command itself...is there any way to safeguard this?

</span>
		</div>
           
    <div class="spacer"></div>

    <div class="rule-gray"></div>
    <div class="spacer-small"></div>

    
            <a name="1233568"></a>
            
	<div valign="top" class="content-listimage">

            
            <div class="size11 darkgray content-meta">
                <div class="floatleft" style="margin-top:-2px; margin-right:10px"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20120626081231/http://it.toolbox.com/people/reality757/"><div class="userimage-defaulttiny"></div></a>
</div>


<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20120626081231/http://it.toolbox.com/people/reality757/" class="size11">Reality757</a>

<!---->

				
<span class="size11 darkgray">Nov 7, 2006</span>
                
                

            </div>
			<span class="anthracite size13" contentbodystyle="Anthracite">By default, atleast on a Fedora system, a common user can't mount anything that isn't specifically defined in the fstab with the user or users tag.  Since chief showed us that the fstab only had local drives listed, that only root could mount this partition.  

</span>
		</div>
           
    <div class="spacer"></div>

    <div class="rule-gray"></div>
